00:30.497 --> 00:34.456
<i>As far as con man stories go,</i>
<i>I think I've heard them all.</i>

00:34.534 --> 00:39.597
<i>Of grifters, ropers, faro-fixers,</i>
<i>tales drawn long and tall.</i>

00:40.540 --> 00:44.340
<i>But if one bears a bookmark</i>
<i>in the confidence man's tome,</i>

00:44.744 --> 00:49.374
<i>it would be that of Penelope,</i>
<i>and of the brothers Bloom.</i>

00:50.050 --> 00:52.678
<i>At 10 and 13, Bloom and Stephen,</i>

00:52.752 --> 00:54.743
<i>the younger and the old,</i>

00:54.821 --> 00:57.619
<i>had been through several foster families.</i>

00:58.992 --> 00:59.981
No!

01:00.360 --> 01:01.884
<i>Thirty-eight, all told.</i>

01:03.363 --> 01:05.593
<i>Mischief moved them on in life,</i>

01:05.665 --> 01:07.860
<i>and moving kept them close.</i>

01:07.934 --> 01:10.835
<i>For Bloom had Stephen,</i>
<i>and Stephen, Bloom,</i>

01:10.904 --> 01:13.031
<i>and both had more than most.</i>

01:14.140 --> 01:16.700
<i>Another home, another Main Street.</i>

01:16.776 --> 01:19.540
<i>Stephen looked around</i>
<i>and summed the burg up thusly.</i>

01:19.612 --> 01:22.410
Bloom, we've hit a one-hat town.

01:22.482 --> 01:26.942
<i>One theater. One car wash. One cafe.</i>
<i>One park. One cat,</i>

01:27.020 --> 01:29.887
<i>which, through some mishap, had one leg.</i>

01:29.956 --> 01:32.015
Sweet Jesus. Look at that.

01:33.193 --> 01:34.217
<i>One public school,</i>

01:34.294 --> 01:37.286
<i>one tight-knit group of local well-off kids.</i>

01:37.397 --> 01:40.093
<i>Their pocket-change bought rocket pops.</i>

01:40.166 --> 01:41.190
<i>The brothers...</i>

01:41.267 --> 01:42.598
Pixy Stix.

01:42.969 --> 01:47.531
<i>They were the they,</i>
<i>all well-loved, rooted, happy as you please,</i>

01:48.475 --> 01:51.137
<i>always there in every town.</i>

01:51.811 --> 01:54.075
Playground bourgeoisies.

02:16.870 --> 02:17.996
<i>Could he simply...</i>

02:18.071 --> 02:19.299
Talk to her!

02:20.573 --> 02:22.734
<i>Just drop his fears and go?</i>

02:23.143 --> 02:26.408
<i>Leave his brother in the woods,</i>
<i>and join the children?</i>

02:29.983 --> 02:31.245
<i>No.</i>

02:31.851 --> 02:36.447
<i>So, in the root of Stephen's psyche,</i>
<i>something now began.</i>

02:36.956 --> 02:41.086
<i>A seed of grand epiphany. A hook. A tale.</i>

02:41.161 --> 02:43.026
- A plan.
<i>- A fiction,</i>

02:43.096 --> 02:46.293
<i>both for profit</i>
<i>and to ease his brother's heart.</i>

02:46.499 --> 02:49.991
<i>A simple con in 15 steps.</i>

02:50.069 --> 02:52.970
And this is where we start.

02:54.674 --> 02:58.974
<i>And then, as if a curtain</i>
<i>had been pulled back from the sky,</i>

03:00.580 --> 03:04.072
<i>some barrier</i>
<i>within the younger Bloom was broken.</i>

03:04.584 --> 03:05.608
Hi.

03:07.687 --> 03:12.351
<i>So Bloom performed his role</i>
<i>in Stephen's story to a T.</i>

03:12.425 --> 03:16.361
<i>And being who he wasn't,</i>
<i>could be as he wished to be.</i>

03:33.513 --> 03:36.573
So, the tale. You tell them...

03:36.649 --> 03:39.083
There's a hermit in the woods.

03:39.152 --> 03:42.121
A one-eyed, steel-toothed vagabond.

03:42.188 --> 03:44.019
- With blood-red eyes?
- That's good.

03:44.090 --> 03:46.320
He stopped you, coming home from school.

03:46.392 --> 03:47.757
And told me of a cave.

03:47.827 --> 03:49.089
What kind of cave?

03:49.162 --> 03:51.096
A cave of wonder.

03:52.298 --> 03:53.424
Shut up, Dave.

03:53.499 --> 03:56.400
At noon on every Sunday,
there appears a ball of light,

03:56.469 --> 03:58.664
which flutters, like a butterfly.

03:58.738 --> 04:00.569
- A will-o'-wisp?
- That's right.

04:00.640 --> 04:01.800
It guides you...

04:01.874 --> 04:03.000
If you can keep up...

04:03.076 --> 04:04.509
...to where the treasures lay.

04:04.577 --> 04:06.568
- So where's this cave?
- Yeah, where?

04:07.847 --> 04:09.576
The hermit didn't say.

04:09.649 --> 04:14.086
He got this greedy,
glinting look, the filthy red-eyed leech,

04:14.153 --> 04:17.850
and said he'd tell for 30 bucks.

04:19.158 --> 04:21.490
Well, that's just 2 bucks each!

04:24.597 --> 04:27.657
<i>And so that Sunday, straight from church,</i>

04:27.734 --> 04:30.294
<i>into the woods Bloom led.</i>

04:35.842 --> 04:40.142
<i>They stopped. Their hearts leapt.</i>
<i>There it was.</i>

04:40.546 --> 04:42.571
Just like the hermit said.

04:58.765 --> 05:02.701
<i>For just one moment,</i>
<i>Bloom forgot himself and ran too fast.</i>

05:02.802 --> 05:05.737
<i>He'd catch the light and find the treasure,</i>

05:07.807 --> 05:09.798
<i>but the moment passed.</i>

05:23.456 --> 05:27.392
<i>They didn't catch the will-o'-wisp,</i>
<i>but didn't really care.</i>

05:27.660 --> 05:30.754
It seems to me that in the end,
the perfect con

05:30.830 --> 05:35.199
is where each one involved
gets just the thing they wanted.

05:36.002 --> 05:38.027
Yeah, I guess so.

05:38.104 --> 05:40.698
<i>Our fledgling thieves were satisfied.</i>

05:42.408 --> 05:44.774
<i>The children's parents, less so.</i>

05:51.884 --> 05:53.909
<i>A bitter ending? Maybe.</i>

05:54.053 --> 05:56.112
<i>But there's sweetness in the mix.</i>

05:56.422 --> 05:59.323
<i>The brothers Bloom had found their calling,</i>

05:59.392 --> 06:01.360
<i>as shown in number six.</i>

06:02.228 --> 06:03.718
<i>"Cut" meant to negotiate.</i>

06:03.796 --> 06:06.060
<i>"Percent," percentage deal.</i>

06:06.132 --> 06:09.533
<i>O'Henry's was the town's</i>
<i>one dry-clean shop.</i>

06:10.236 --> 06:12.830
Pleasure doing business with you.

06:15.408 --> 06:17.035
So how's it feel?

06:18.578 --> 06:22.605
<i>In truth, young Bloom</i>
<i>won't know for 20 years just how he felt.</i>

06:22.682 --> 06:25.310
<i>And so, we'll skip ahead now in our story.</i>

06:25.385 --> 06:26.852
Let 'em melt.

07:16.369 --> 07:17.734
He gets the scarab,

07:17.804 --> 07:20.466
you get the money, and I get the girl.

07:20.573 --> 07:23.804
So in the end,
everyone gets everything he wants.

07:27.246 --> 07:28.508
Victor!

07:31.684 --> 07:36.178
Charleston, what have you done?
Oh, my God.

07:38.057 --> 07:40.082
Oh, God, he's dead!

07:40.593 --> 07:43.084
He was the only one who knew
where our money was buried,

07:43.162 --> 07:47.121
and you shot him! Charleston, you dunce!

07:49.001 --> 07:51.162
The man named Charleston that you met

07:51.270 --> 07:53.363
four months and 1,000 years ago

07:53.439 --> 07:55.566
in a hotel bar in Jodhpur is dead.

07:56.509 --> 08:00.138
If we see each other again,
it'll be as strangers.

08:00.680 --> 08:02.807
As for the money,

08:06.385 --> 08:08.080
let it rot.

08:39.352 --> 08:40.683
Wow!

08:41.187 --> 08:44.816
"Wow" is the word you're looking for! Wow!

08:46.959 --> 08:48.756
You're a genius, Stephen.

08:48.828 --> 08:50.728
We're genius, Bloom.

08:52.331 --> 08:55.960
<i>Now, in defense of that shit-eating</i>
<i>grin on my older brother's face,</i>

08:56.035 --> 08:58.731
<i>what he just pulled off was pretty amazing.</i>

08:58.804 --> 09:01.739
<i>He hinged the entire con on this question.</i>

09:02.141 --> 09:04.632
<i>Would Charleston, our spineless mark,</i>

09:04.777 --> 09:07.302
<i>would he actually pull that trigger?</i>

09:08.581 --> 09:10.048
<i>Maybe.</i>

09:10.116 --> 09:11.674
<i>But Stephen wanted better odds.</i>

09:11.751 --> 09:14.242
<i>He positioned me in the same spot where,</i>
<i>six years ago,</i>

09:14.320 --> 09:16.880
<i>Charleston's wife had stood</i>
<i>and told him she was leaving.</i>

09:16.956 --> 09:18.924
<i>He picked my suit to match her outfit.</i>

09:18.991 --> 09:22.017
<i>He even phonetically matched</i>
<i>my final words to hers.</i>

09:22.094 --> 09:24.289
This is the end, Charleston.

09:24.430 --> 09:26.660
You've always been such a dunce.

09:26.799 --> 09:30.030
So in the end,
everyone gets everything he wants.

09:32.204 --> 09:33.535
Tastes like tinfoil.

09:33.606 --> 09:35.073
So does real blood.

09:35.708 --> 09:36.868
Buy you a drink?

09:41.247 --> 09:43.772
Nine months and 1,000 years ago.

09:43.849 --> 09:47.376
He was quoting from Kipling.
He stole that from Kipling.

09:47.887 --> 09:49.354
No, he didn't.

09:49.422 --> 09:51.322
So where's this wrap party?

09:51.390 --> 09:54.723
Make way, make room
for the brothers Bloom!

09:56.796 --> 09:58.593
Yeah, yeah!

10:00.633 --> 10:03.534
All right, here we go.
Gather round, friends and accomplices.

10:03.603 --> 10:06.572
Think of a card. You got it?

10:09.175 --> 10:10.301
No.

10:10.376 --> 10:12.674
If I do it enough,
someday it's gonna work on someone.

10:12.745 --> 10:16.272
And then it'll be
the best damn card trick in the world.

10:17.016 --> 10:20.144
It's true you never work
with the same crew twice?

10:20.219 --> 10:22.119
Well, shit. Except for the...

10:22.188 --> 10:23.212
Bang Bang?

10:23.289 --> 10:25.883
You know, I'm pretty big into anime.

10:26.158 --> 10:28.319
She's our fifth Beatle.

10:29.028 --> 10:31.155
She knows the ins and outs.

10:31.597 --> 10:34.657
I don't think she speaks
more than three words of English.

10:34.734 --> 10:35.792
Campari.

10:35.868 --> 10:38.769
So, she's with you and Bloom till the end?

10:38.838 --> 10:40.703
Till the wind changes.

11:03.396 --> 11:04.920
Where is Bloom?

11:18.644 --> 11:20.373
There you are.

11:20.713 --> 11:21.771
You hiding?

11:22.148 --> 11:23.206
Yep.

11:23.349 --> 11:25.249
I've been learning.

11:25.451 --> 11:27.351
Stephen likes to talk about you.

11:27.486 --> 11:29.386
He tell you the cave story?

11:29.622 --> 11:30.987
Is it true?

11:32.058 --> 11:34.117
What else did he tell you?

11:35.094 --> 11:38.154
You two kicked around until your early teens

11:38.230 --> 11:41.859
winding up in the grotty outskirts
of St. Petersburg,

11:42.501 --> 11:47.598
where you learned the big con from an
old-school grifter named the Diamond Dog.

11:47.907 --> 11:49.465
Is that true?

11:49.742 --> 11:51.937
- That was his name?
- Yep.

11:52.511 --> 11:54.672
And he was your mentor.

11:55.314 --> 11:57.805
But I get the sense it ended badly.

11:58.217 --> 12:01.311
Stephen took his eye out
with an antique rapier.

12:01.854 --> 12:03.583
Why did he do that?

12:03.689 --> 12:06.157
The brothers Bloom lit out on their own

12:06.292 --> 12:08.760
to make their fortune as gentleman thieves.

12:09.462 --> 12:11.089
Sounds romantic.

12:12.231 --> 12:13.459
It does.

12:23.743 --> 12:26.541
You don't understand what my brother does.

12:30.082 --> 12:33.518
He writes his cons
the way dead Russians write novels,

12:33.586 --> 12:37.215
with thematic arcs
and embedded symbolism and shit.

12:38.657 --> 12:41.649
And he wrote me as the vulnerable antihero.

12:44.263 --> 12:47.164
And that's why you think you wanna kiss me.

12:49.835 --> 12:51.200
It's a con.

12:58.110 --> 12:59.668
I'm going nuts.

13:03.282 --> 13:05.045
There's the big two.

13:15.861 --> 13:17.886
We missed the sunrise.

13:18.731 --> 13:20.995
That would have been nice.

13:32.311 --> 13:34.074
Is this the bathroom?

13:35.915 --> 13:37.780
No. This is camels.

13:38.984 --> 13:41.179
Hold on, I must make piss.

14:01.006 --> 14:03.201
At least you're honest. All right, let's do this.

14:03.275 --> 14:05.675
Let's just get it done. So, first you say,

14:05.744 --> 14:08.838
"I'm quitting, Stephen. I'm out." Then I say...

14:08.914 --> 14:10.973
- Do we have to go through this again?
- "Go through this again?"

14:11.050 --> 14:13.109
And then you make a show
of putting on your jacket,

14:13.185 --> 14:15.551
and you say, " No,
I mean it this time, Stephen.

14:15.621 --> 14:17.486
"This time, I'm really out."

14:17.556 --> 14:19.114
And then you say, "Let's have a drink,"

14:19.191 --> 14:22.991
"and in the morning, Bloom,
you'll have come to your senses."

14:23.696 --> 14:25.459
It's a major design
flaw in fake blood, by the way.

14:25.531 --> 14:27.465
- "And we'll be moving on."
- Real blood turns brown...

14:27.533 --> 14:28.898
- Listen to me, Stephen. I...
...after half an hour.

14:28.968 --> 14:30.663
This Scotch cost more than your suit.

14:30.736 --> 14:31.896
Listen to me.

14:32.037 --> 14:33.197
The flask stopped a bullet in Normandy.

14:33.272 --> 14:34.432
Listen!

14:39.345 --> 14:40.676
Holy shit.

14:42.548 --> 14:44.880
That's my new favorite camel.

14:50.990 --> 14:52.890
I hate you. Okay?

14:58.530 --> 15:01.931
Oh, God, I can't do this anymore.

15:02.001 --> 15:05.937
I can't wake up next to another person
who thinks they know me.

15:06.238 --> 15:08.536
And I'm 35 years old. I don't...

15:08.607 --> 15:10.837
I'm useless. I'm crippled.

15:11.310 --> 15:12.743
I don't...

15:13.445 --> 15:16.972
I've only ever lived life
through these roles that aren't me,

15:17.049 --> 15:19.381
that are written for me by you.

15:21.387 --> 15:23.014
Tell me what you want.

15:23.088 --> 15:25.921
Why? So you can write me a role
in a story where I get it?

15:25.991 --> 15:28.255
You're not listening to me!

15:28.327 --> 15:32.161
I want a real thing.

15:33.365 --> 15:35.333
I want a...

15:36.001 --> 15:38.731
I just... I want... I... want...

15:41.941 --> 15:45.468
- You want an unwritten life.
- I want an unwritten life.

15:50.482 --> 15:51.949
I'm going away,

15:52.017 --> 15:53.211
somewhere where you and Bang Bang

15:53.285 --> 15:54.411
won't even be able to track me down.

15:54.486 --> 15:57.717
So don't try it, okay? No more stories.

16:00.359 --> 16:02.623
I love you. Goodbye.

16:54.113 --> 16:55.205
How'd you find me?

16:55.347 --> 16:56.473
Bang Bang.

16:58.183 --> 16:59.946
How'd she find me?

17:02.121 --> 17:03.782
How you been?

17:05.590 --> 17:06.785
Great.

17:10.796 --> 17:14.196
I've been doing a lot of thinking
the past three months,

17:14.266 --> 17:17.291
and I've come to the conclusion
that you don't want out.

17:17.368 --> 17:19.859
You think you do, but you don't.

17:21.440 --> 17:24.034
Hey, come here.
I wanna show you something.

17:24.108 --> 17:25.804
I'm quit, Stephen.

17:31.750 --> 17:33.240
Where are we going?

17:33.318 --> 17:34.580
New Jersey.

17:36.121 --> 17:37.884
Let me grab my coat.

17:46.298 --> 17:48.892
So, where are we?

17:49.134 --> 17:51.967
The largest private residence
on the Eastern Seaboard,

17:52.037 --> 17:54.232
home of our final mark.

17:54.306 --> 17:56.365
Daddy was an oil tycoon, a Hearst type,

17:56.442 --> 17:59.809
built a Xanadu to match,
then died hunting quail.

18:00.245 --> 18:03.305
Mom followed
into the hereafter two years ago,

18:03.382 --> 18:06.909
after 10 years of fighting a disease
that I can't even pronounce.

18:06.985 --> 18:12.048
Thank you. Leaving our sucker all alone
on this ludicrous estate

18:13.759 --> 18:15.249
with an insane amount of very liquid assets.

18:15.327 --> 18:17.625
What the hell is that?
What are we, near an airport? What is that?

18:17.696 --> 18:18.788
Duck.

18:24.103 --> 18:25.593
What the hell?

19:06.145 --> 19:07.339
Get the car.

19:07.412 --> 19:10.438
- Bloom.
- No women. One rule.

19:10.649 --> 19:12.139
You know we don't do women.

19:12.217 --> 19:14.242
And it's not a morality thing or a thing.

19:14.319 --> 19:16.810
It's... Whatever it is,
it doesn't matter what it is,

19:16.889 --> 19:20.882
it's just our rule. So what are we...
Is this a '78 Caddy?

19:21.560 --> 19:23.221
Controversial choice.

19:23.295 --> 19:26.890
So no, is what I'm saying, all right?
I'm quits, anyway.

19:26.965 --> 19:29.297
I'll be in Montenegro, drinking.

19:31.003 --> 19:35.667
Ah, Penelope Stamp, 33.

19:36.141 --> 19:38.439
Lived at home her whole life.

19:41.914 --> 19:45.145
An eccentric shut-in rich bitch?
You're not helping your case.

19:45.217 --> 19:48.675
She's bored. She's a little seed in the snow.

19:48.754 --> 19:51.416
We're going to put her on a grand adventure,
bring her to life.

19:51.490 --> 19:53.287
She needs sprouting.

19:56.695 --> 19:58.720
So this is the big plan, huh?

19:58.797 --> 20:04.531
Lure me back in with some beautiful,
intriguing, elusive girl.

20:09.241 --> 20:12.506
Seriously, Stephen. Amateur night.

20:22.020 --> 20:24.682
I'm not saying yes, but what's the con?

20:24.756 --> 20:28.021
It's actually pretty simple.
We're brothers, antiquities dealers.

20:28.093 --> 20:30.220
We're traveling the world by steamer ship.

20:30.295 --> 20:33.924
Bang! Give her
the old cackle-bladder and the brush-off.

20:34.666 --> 20:36.133
And that's how it ends in Mexico,

20:36.201 --> 20:39.693
burst of violence,
then a moment of truth on the beach.

20:39.972 --> 20:41.769
What do you think?

20:41.840 --> 20:43.671
You got something up your sleeve.

20:44.843 --> 20:48.244
This is about me, right? Somehow.

20:52.050 --> 20:53.779
Now, this might not be
something that you know,

20:53.852 --> 20:56.184
but they've all been about you.

20:58.090 --> 21:00.388
Maybe that's why they've none been perfect,

21:00.459 --> 21:04.418
because I've never been
able to give you what you really wanted.

21:04.830 --> 21:07.458
This isn't gonna give me what I want.

21:21.513 --> 21:23.538
This will be the last one.

21:25.851 --> 21:26.875
You'll let me go.

21:26.952 --> 21:29.284
I'll never ask you to do another con again.

21:33.058 --> 21:34.923
Make it a Schwinn.

21:47.973 --> 21:51.568
There are less painful ways
to cut into a mark, you know.

21:53.545 --> 21:55.570
Score to beat is 7.9.

21:55.647 --> 21:59.481
Keep your head in the game.
The Japanese judge is very tough.

21:59.551 --> 22:01.678
This is a banana seat, man!

22:03.789 --> 22:04.949
Don't give me that blank look,

22:05.023 --> 22:07.321
you know what a goddamn banana seat is.

22:07.392 --> 22:08.620
Oh!

22:15.300 --> 22:16.460
Shit.

22:25.744 --> 22:26.836
Shit!

22:37.389 --> 22:38.583
<i>There's actually a knack to this.</i>

22:38.657 --> 22:41.683
<i>If you're trying to fast track</i>
<i>into a mark's sympathies,</i>

22:41.760 --> 22:44.126
<i>there's nothing quite as effective</i>

22:44.196 --> 22:46.528
<i>as having your first conversation</i>

22:46.598 --> 22:49.965
<i>be from a hospital bed they put you in.</i>

23:02.981 --> 23:06.246
What? Oh, come on.

23:55.534 --> 23:59.664
I actually think this is kind of
a great thing, and I'll tell you why.

24:00.172 --> 24:02.436
Dostoevsky was an epileptic.

24:03.341 --> 24:06.003
His seizures were preceded
by an enlightened euphoria,

24:06.077 --> 24:08.272
a sort of opening of his spiritual eye.

24:08.346 --> 24:12.214
I think the fact that she saw your face
the instant before a seizure

24:12.284 --> 24:16.050
is a pretty goddamn good foot
to start things off on, right?

24:22.394 --> 24:23.918
<i>The next step,</i>

24:23.995 --> 24:27.123
<i>is to figure out a way to insinuate yourself</i>
<i>into their personal life.</i>

24:29.801 --> 24:34.135
I think they took my car.
Could you drive me home?

24:37.309 --> 24:39.038
- Yeah.
- Okay.

24:39.811 --> 24:41.574
I'm gonna...

24:59.164 --> 25:01.530
<i>Step three, engagement.</i>

25:01.600 --> 25:04.501
<i>Find a connection with your mark</i>
<i>through conversation.</i>

25:04.569 --> 25:07.470
<i>Get invited in for coffee.</i>
<i>Tell them the full tale.</i>

25:07.539 --> 25:09.006
<i>Set your hook.</i>

25:09.074 --> 25:12.043
...didn't really have anyone
except each other growing up,

25:12.110 --> 25:16.513
and our father was in the antique business.
He had a shop in Charleston.

25:17.082 --> 25:20.017
We realized one day we saw the dealers

25:20.085 --> 25:22.918
who were finding and selling us the antiques

25:22.988 --> 25:26.890
coming from exotic countries,

25:27.959 --> 25:29.927
around the world, and...

25:30.695 --> 25:33.289
The air would, like,

25:33.965 --> 25:36.991
before a rain, you know,
the ions would line up,

25:37.068 --> 25:39.127
and you could just

25:42.374 --> 25:45.468
smell midnight trains to Paris

25:46.711 --> 25:50.772
and steamer ships
and Calcutta bazaars, and...

25:55.687 --> 25:58.815
It could... Excuse me, I'm sorry, uh...

25:59.090 --> 26:00.887
- Are you okay?
- Yeah!

26:01.526 --> 26:03.357
- Sorry.
- Okay. All right.

26:03.428 --> 26:05.055
I'm really bad at talking to people.

26:05.130 --> 26:06.688
That's okay.

26:10.869 --> 26:11.858
You want me to go?

26:11.937 --> 26:14.804
No. No, I really want to talk to you.

26:30.221 --> 26:31.347
So...

26:33.325 --> 26:35.520
What kind of stuff do you do?

26:36.928 --> 26:40.591
Nothing. Maybe you should go.

26:41.833 --> 26:43.232
All right, I'll just finish my...

26:43.301 --> 26:44.962
I collect hobbies.

26:45.804 --> 26:48.272
I see someone doing something I like,

26:48.406 --> 26:50.897
and I get books and I learn how to do it.

26:51.042 --> 26:52.031
Hmm.

26:52.978 --> 26:55.003
Anything interesting?

26:56.848 --> 26:58.213
Not really.

27:25.944 --> 27:29.141
<i>Like he had a disease</i>
<i>He robbed another and another and a...</i>

27:29.214 --> 27:31.273
- I really am not comfortable with this at all.
- I throw my right chainsaw...

27:31.349 --> 27:33.840
- This is a running chainsaw.
...into the air and I will catch.

27:43.928 --> 27:46.897
You just learn this stuff here by yourself?

27:49.067 --> 27:50.534
Kind of sad?

27:50.602 --> 27:51.796
No.

27:55.407 --> 27:57.932
So, how do you plan to use all these skills?

27:58.009 --> 28:01.501
I don't know. I'm not a planner.
I just do stuff.

28:02.347 --> 28:07.182
Like, look at this watermelon.
It's a pinhole camera.

28:07.252 --> 28:11.348
You can make a pinhole camera
out of anything hollow and dark.

28:12.891 --> 28:15.621
It's gotta warp the image though, right?

28:15.860 --> 28:17.555
Yeah, yeah it does.

28:17.696 --> 28:19.391
I mean, that's what's good about it.

28:19.964 --> 28:22.023
I mean, you could point this baby

28:22.167 --> 28:24.226
at the most menial, everyday little thing,

28:24.302 --> 28:27.328
like the fabric, or your...

28:29.441 --> 28:31.170
Your face, or anything,

28:31.242 --> 28:33.472
and depending on
how the pinhole eats the light,

28:33.545 --> 28:38.414
it's gonna be warped and peculiar
and imperfect and odd,

28:38.483 --> 28:41.919
and it's not gonna be reproduction,

28:41.986 --> 28:44.978
it's storytelling.

28:46.558 --> 28:48.549
It's a lie that tells the truth.

28:48.626 --> 28:50.560
I don't know about truths.

28:51.029 --> 28:53.327
A photograph is a secret about a secret.

28:53.465 --> 28:55.763
The more it tells you, less you know.

28:58.169 --> 29:00.228
What's changed between now
and 20 minutes ago?

29:00.305 --> 29:03.672
'Cause this is sort of like a conversation.

29:06.811 --> 29:08.403
Well, shit.

29:21.059 --> 29:24.051
<i>Throw my ticket out the window</i>

29:26.998 --> 29:29.967
<i>Throw my suitcase out there, too</i>

29:34.339 --> 29:37.331
<i>Throw my troubles out the door</i>

29:37.542 --> 29:40.204
<i>I don't need them anymore</i>

29:40.311 --> 29:43.212
<i>'Cause tonight I'll be staying here with you</i>

29:43.281 --> 29:45.078
Well...

29:45.150 --> 29:46.549
I should...

29:47.952 --> 29:49.283
It's late.

29:49.921 --> 29:51.582
- So...
- So...

29:54.259 --> 29:56.557
I meet a lot of people in my job

29:56.628 --> 29:58.858
I have to professionally act interested in.

30:00.698 --> 30:04.361
It's a good feeling
to be genuinely interested in someone.

30:06.738 --> 30:08.330
Are you leaving?

30:10.041 --> 30:11.338
Yeah.

30:11.509 --> 30:12.533
Oh.

30:12.911 --> 30:14.310
Coming back?

30:14.712 --> 30:16.839
Well, next time I'm in town.

30:17.849 --> 30:20.545
We're taking a steamer at noon tomorrow
off the docks,

30:20.618 --> 30:22.848
to the continent for a few months.

30:22.921 --> 30:24.946
Paris and Greece, I think.

30:27.058 --> 30:28.923
I've got to get a hat.

30:29.227 --> 30:33.163
Well, thanks for
the pinhole camera demonstration.

30:33.231 --> 30:36.860
And the good conversation.

30:39.604 --> 30:40.935
All right.

30:44.409 --> 30:46.070
Goodbye, Penelope.

30:46.611 --> 30:48.169
Goodbye, Bloom.

31:05.163 --> 31:07.996
She isn't coming, man.
I need another day with her.

31:08.066 --> 31:09.761
You'll have two weeks with her on the boat.

31:09.834 --> 31:11.699
I need another day to get her on the boat.

31:11.769 --> 31:13.464
She's not hooked. I've had one session,

31:13.538 --> 31:17.201
and we mostly talked watermelons
and the optics of lensless photography.

31:17.275 --> 31:19.937
It's not the talking that hooked her.

31:20.011 --> 31:21.239
I think you're wrong.

31:21.646 --> 31:22.840
Hey, get out of the street, idiot!

31:24.048 --> 31:25.242
Watch it!

31:34.259 --> 31:36.124
- Hey.
- Hi.

31:39.664 --> 31:41.757
What are you doing here?

31:41.833 --> 31:42.822
Uh...

31:45.703 --> 31:50.367
I wanna give you this money
for the bike and for the whole thing.

31:50.441 --> 31:53.604
- That's all right. It's not necessary, really.
- Oh.

31:57.949 --> 32:00.713
Hey, where is this boat going?

32:23.408 --> 32:26.343
Penelope, my brother Stephen.

32:26.411 --> 32:28.572
Glad to make your acquaintance.

32:28.646 --> 32:30.307
Bloom's told me so much about you.

32:30.381 --> 32:32.941
You're the epileptic photographer?

32:33.017 --> 32:34.348
Sort of.

32:34.652 --> 32:36.950
And this is my personal assistant

32:38.122 --> 32:40.716
and private masseuse, Mrs. Yueng Ling.

32:41.259 --> 32:42.692
Yuengling like the beer?

32:42.827 --> 32:44.260
No.

32:49.400 --> 32:51.334
So, what are your plans in Greece?

32:51.402 --> 32:53.529
- I don't plan.
- Good for you.

33:08.586 --> 33:13.387
<i>When they begin the beguine</i>

33:14.959 --> 33:19.987
<i>It brings back the sound of music so tender</i>

33:20.498 --> 33:22.227
You look very nice.

33:22.300 --> 33:27.033
<i>It brings back a night of tropical splendor</i>

33:28.339 --> 33:32.799
<i>It brings back a memory of green</i>

33:36.214 --> 33:38.409
What was your childhood like?

33:39.017 --> 33:41.542
I made cameras out of watermelons.

33:43.354 --> 33:44.616
Lonely?

33:48.393 --> 33:54.127
When I was five, I got really bad rashes
and allergies and hay fever.

33:55.299 --> 33:57.597
So my mom took me to the doctor,

33:57.668 --> 33:59.602
and he did that test

33:59.670 --> 34:03.071
where they use needles
to prick a grid on your back

34:03.307 --> 34:05.571
with different toxins on them, you know,

34:05.643 --> 34:07.873
to see which ones you're allergic to.

34:07.945 --> 34:10.914
Next day I come in,
the doctor lifts up my shirt,

34:10.982 --> 34:12.847
and my back is a patch of oily, moldy,

34:12.917 --> 34:15.681
blackish-green double-puff marshmallows.

34:16.487 --> 34:18.819
I was allergic to everything.

34:19.956 --> 34:22.152
So they sealed the house with plastic

34:22.226 --> 34:24.353
and a special ventilation system,

34:24.429 --> 34:28.058
and I spent the rest of my childhood
and adolescence indoors.

34:28.132 --> 34:29.565
Alone.

34:30.601 --> 34:31.829
Lonely.

34:32.670 --> 34:34.570
- Wow.
- It wasn't till I was 19

34:34.639 --> 34:39.804
they discovered what I was
actually allergic to was the aluminum alloy

34:39.877 --> 34:42.641
the hypodermic needles were made out of.

34:44.248 --> 34:46.341
Then I was gonna leave,

34:47.351 --> 34:49.978
but my mom got sick. So I stayed.

34:51.089 --> 34:53.956
She stayed sick a really long time.

34:54.992 --> 34:56.391
Do you...

34:58.329 --> 34:59.819
Feel cheated?

35:00.364 --> 35:04.198
The trick to not feeling cheated
is to learn how to cheat.

35:04.635 --> 35:06.068
So,

35:06.537 --> 35:10.439
I decided this wasn't a story
about a miserable girl

35:10.508 --> 35:13.944
trapped in a house that
smelled like medical supplies,

35:14.278 --> 35:18.908
wasting her life on a dying person
she sometimes hated. No.

35:20.051 --> 35:25.614
This was a story about a girl who could find
infinite beauty in anything,

35:26.557 --> 35:28.184
any little thing.

35:29.026 --> 35:32.018
And even love the person
she was trapped with.

35:33.264 --> 35:36.529
And I told myself this story
until it became true.

35:38.870 --> 35:43.705
Now, did doing this help me
escape a wasted life,

35:43.774 --> 35:48.108
or did it blind me
so I wouldn't want to escape it?

35:48.179 --> 35:51.273
I don't know. But either way,

35:51.349 --> 35:54.147
I was the one telling my own story, so...

35:55.253 --> 35:58.711
No, I don't feel cheated at all.

36:12.336 --> 36:14.668
I don't suppose in all your hobby-acquiring,

36:14.739 --> 36:16.969
you ever learned how to dance?

36:17.308 --> 36:21.404
I went through a phase when I was mildly
obsessed with the bolero.

36:21.979 --> 36:23.503
Give me a minute.

37:01.586 --> 37:05.920
It's a long time since I last encountered
the brothers Bloom.

37:08.159 --> 37:09.956
Are you in antiques?

37:14.599 --> 37:15.896
Antique?

37:17.001 --> 37:21.495
I wonder, my dear, if you know
the true nature of the men you travel with.

37:29.213 --> 37:31.841
A little fear might suit you, I think.

37:50.534 --> 37:53.833
It isn't a Spanish band,
but they'll do their best.

38:43.554 --> 38:44.543
Mmm...

38:57.902 --> 39:00.871
And then... This is the really important part.

39:00.938 --> 39:02.701
You have to make a little,
itty-bitty, little hole.

39:11.816 --> 39:14.512
The ship's too small for us
to be dancing around each other.

39:14.585 --> 39:17.076
We might as well have this out now.

39:17.521 --> 39:19.955
Penelope, do you know our friend?

39:20.658 --> 39:22.523
Only as the creepy Frenchman.

39:22.593 --> 39:24.925
Book-learned. You know your languages

39:24.995 --> 39:26.553
but not your accents, <i>mademoiselle.</i>

39:26.630 --> 39:29.064
- No, I am Belgian.
- Ah.

39:29.500 --> 39:32.162
Maximilian Melville, at your service.

39:32.236 --> 39:35.899
Also known in certain professional circles
as The Curator.

39:35.973 --> 39:38.703
Pleased to make your acquaintance.
What do you do?

39:38.776 --> 39:43.770
I am a curator, presently at
the National <i>Musée</i> in Prague.

39:43.848 --> 39:45.475
Yeah. And yourself?

39:45.549 --> 39:47.210
I'm an epileptic photographer.

39:48.085 --> 39:51.612
Good for you. And you boys?
What do you do?

39:51.689 --> 39:54.453
We run a legitimate
antique reselling business.

39:54.525 --> 39:55.514
Ah.

39:59.397 --> 40:01.024
We've gone straight, Max.

40:01.098 --> 40:05.626
<i>Pardon,</i> but why would you ascend to
the great heights of the brothers Bloom

40:05.703 --> 40:08.399
just to toss it away, huh? To do what?

40:09.140 --> 40:13.304
To sell terra cotta
to blue-haired weekend antiquers?

40:13.377 --> 40:16.278
- I don't think so.
- We did. Eat your waffles.

40:17.681 --> 40:21.481
You know, the <i>mademoiselle,</i>
she seems a little confused.

40:21.552 --> 40:23.042
Maybe she is unawares?

40:23.120 --> 40:24.644
Eat your waffles, fat man.

40:25.790 --> 40:28.588
Unawares that the brothers Bloom, in fact,

40:29.994 --> 40:32.861
are the two most respected

40:34.198 --> 40:37.167
smugglers of antiques in the Western world.

40:37.768 --> 40:41.795
Were. We've been on
the straight for three years. So that's that.

40:41.872 --> 40:45.968
Oh, oh. Well, if that is that,
then that indeed is that. If you say so.

40:47.378 --> 40:48.367
Oh.

40:50.014 --> 40:52.482
- Your name's Melville.
<i>- Oui, vrai.</i>

40:53.317 --> 40:54.511
Right.

40:55.586 --> 40:59.386
No, sorry, um,
'cause I noticed before but I couldn't place it.

40:59.457 --> 41:01.049
This ship is called the <i>Fidele,</i>

41:01.125 --> 41:06.188
which is the name of the ship
in Melville's novel, <i>The Confidence-Man.</i>

41:07.198 --> 41:09.428
- So that's weird.
<i>- Oui.</i>

41:14.505 --> 41:16.700
I have never read that.

41:22.112 --> 41:26.242
Smugglers. It's like an adventure story.

41:27.485 --> 41:29.953
Whose idea was it to go straight?

41:30.287 --> 41:33.688
Mine. Stephen always loved the life.

41:34.291 --> 41:38.022
Then he was almost killed
on a run to Jakarta.

41:38.896 --> 41:41.626
These two thugs
with heads like canned hams

41:41.699 --> 41:43.530
worked him beyond all reason.

41:43.601 --> 41:46.297
Have at me, you ham-headed bastard!

41:47.404 --> 41:48.428
Shit!

41:48.639 --> 41:52.006
Sometimes I think he'd love to die on a job.

41:52.576 --> 41:55.409
Cornered at midnight on a run to Jakarta.

41:56.380 --> 41:58.211
That's his dream,

41:58.716 --> 42:01.549
to tell a story so well it fulfills itself.

42:03.220 --> 42:04.482
Somehow.

42:06.223 --> 42:08.987
It would finally make it real for him.

42:09.493 --> 42:12.121
That's kind of the thing we all want.

42:14.999 --> 42:19.993
Well, trying to get something real by telling
yourself stories is a trap.

42:21.105 --> 42:22.868
Trust me on that one.

42:36.353 --> 42:38.685
She's different. She knows...

42:40.190 --> 42:43.284
Sometimes I feel like she knows everything.

42:43.594 --> 42:45.528
Doesn't that worry you?

42:45.930 --> 42:49.229
No, but something about her
is worrying you plenty.

42:50.267 --> 42:52.895
She feels like one of your characters.

42:59.510 --> 43:02.343
The day I con you is the day I die, Bloom.

43:05.182 --> 43:08.083
How'd you get the Belgian on our budget?

43:08.385 --> 43:10.285
He's beautiful, right?

43:10.487 --> 43:12.387
I didn't expect him to actually be Belgian.

43:12.456 --> 43:14.947
I'm not sure he is. I'm off to bed.

43:16.694 --> 43:17.786
Hey.

43:19.563 --> 43:21.997
The only real danger in this whole play

43:22.132 --> 43:24.600
is that you actually fall in love with her.

43:24.668 --> 43:26.295
Hey, look at me.

43:27.004 --> 43:29.564
Mexico is closer than you think.

43:30.240 --> 43:32.731
Don't fall in love with her, Bloom.

43:46.991 --> 43:49.892
Good luck, boys, with the antiquing, huh.

44:06.977 --> 44:08.444
My French is a little rusty,

44:08.512 --> 44:12.107
but I believe he said,
"My proposition stands."

44:12.182 --> 44:14.650
He came out of nowhere last night.

44:14.918 --> 44:17.386
<i>Mademoiselle,</i> I will make you a proposition.

44:17.454 --> 44:19.115
Oh, Lord. What has he got?

44:19.189 --> 44:21.157
An 8th-century prayer book.

44:21.225 --> 44:23.523
He steals pieces from his museum in Prague,

44:23.594 --> 44:25.585
<i>and sells them off through smugglers.</i>

44:25.663 --> 44:26.755
That's what he does.

44:26.830 --> 44:28.161
I wonder who's his fence?

44:28.298 --> 44:29.629
It's probably his Spanish guy, right?

44:29.700 --> 44:30.689
Did he say who's buying?

44:30.768 --> 44:34.226
Yeah, an Argentinean. Argentine? Argent...

44:34.304 --> 44:36.602
A gentleman from the Argentine.

44:36.907 --> 44:41.844
So, The Curator will sell it to a middleman
for $1 million US,

44:41.979 --> 44:46.439
and then the Argentine...
The guy from South America,

44:46.517 --> 44:49.281
he will pay $2.5.

44:50.954 --> 44:52.478
It's not bad.

44:53.057 --> 44:55.787
I'm sorry you had to deal with that guy.

44:57.027 --> 44:58.551
Where's that cab going?

44:59.196 --> 45:00.720
Train station.

45:01.365 --> 45:02.423
Where's the train going?

45:02.499 --> 45:03.659
Prague.

45:05.836 --> 45:09.237
Come on! Let's be smugglers.

45:09.306 --> 45:11.831
I mean, I think it'd be fun. We should do this.

45:11.909 --> 45:13.809
- No.
- Why not?

45:14.178 --> 45:16.169
Well, first off, we don't have $1 million.

45:17.281 --> 45:18.976
That's like, I've got, what... That's whatever.

45:19.049 --> 45:20.607
I mean, give me a real reason.

45:20.684 --> 45:22.549
This is real. It's dangerous.

45:24.455 --> 45:26.821
- This could go very bad.
- Hmm.

45:27.391 --> 45:30.360
Well, I think
a little real danger might suit me,

45:30.427 --> 45:33.055
so, if you three want to join
my smugglers gang,

45:33.130 --> 45:35.655
I'II, you know, consider it.

45:38.135 --> 45:40.399
This isn't an adventure story.

45:40.604 --> 45:43.368
What are you talking about?

45:43.474 --> 45:45.442
Well, it totally is!

45:59.123 --> 46:02.115
Go, go, go. Go, go.

46:02.192 --> 46:03.386
You there, come back here!

46:04.428 --> 46:06.055
This is not for free.

46:15.739 --> 46:16.763
Wait up. Where are you?

46:16.840 --> 46:18.808
Come here. Come here.

46:21.879 --> 46:23.540
We're smuggling.

46:26.150 --> 46:27.913
From the snack car.

46:31.054 --> 46:33.614
She's making a flag
for our smugglers gang, man.

46:33.690 --> 46:36.750
This afternoon,
when she was writing in the observation car,

46:36.827 --> 46:38.988
I thought she was writing a letter, a journal.

46:39.062 --> 46:41.496
No. Come on, she's getting way too into this.

46:42.666 --> 46:45.897
It's not funny. I don't like this Prague con
you've cooked up, either.

46:46.403 --> 46:47.597
You're just leaving too much to chance.

46:47.671 --> 46:48.831
Listen, the whole point of this

46:48.906 --> 46:50.533
was to sweep her off her feet.

46:50.607 --> 46:52.370
So why don't you let her enjoy it?

46:52.442 --> 46:54.000
While it lasts?

47:03.720 --> 47:05.813
This came through just now?

47:06.990 --> 47:09.185
"Dear Stephen. Stop. Word on the wire is..."

47:09.259 --> 47:12.023
<i>"...The brothers B.</i>
<i>are bound for Prague.</i>

47:12.095 --> 47:13.585
<i>"I'm heading there myself.</i>

47:13.664 --> 47:17.828
<i>"Would love to see my boys.</i>
<i>Affectionately, D. D."</i>

47:17.901 --> 47:21.359
Our old Fagin is back. The Diamond Dog.

47:22.239 --> 47:23.729
Wire him back for me.

47:23.807 --> 47:25.536
Dear Dog. Stop.

47:25.609 --> 47:28.737
Unless you feel an excess of eyeballs
left in your skull,

47:28.812 --> 47:32.771
I highly suggest you stay far away from
me and my brother. Stop.

47:33.350 --> 47:36.513
Affectionately... Et cetera.

47:48.565 --> 47:50.863
You've taken this train before?

47:51.635 --> 47:52.727
- Yeah.
- Hmm.

47:53.470 --> 47:56.405
So this is all just like, "Whatever" to you.

47:56.473 --> 47:58.805
Well, I mean, usually, I'd just, you know,

47:58.876 --> 48:01.367
play cards and drink with Bang Bang
in the snack car.

48:01.445 --> 48:02.742
Bang who?

48:04.982 --> 48:06.506
Yueng Ling.

48:06.583 --> 48:09.017
- Bang Bang's her smuggler nickname.
- Ah.

48:09.953 --> 48:11.580
So how about me?

48:12.055 --> 48:13.283
Do I get a smuggler nickname?

48:13.357 --> 48:14.517
No.

48:21.865 --> 48:24.060
I think you're constipated.

48:25.369 --> 48:27.166
In your fucking soul.

48:32.576 --> 48:33.907
I think

48:34.378 --> 48:39.748
you might have a really big load of grumpy,
petrified poop up your soul's ass.

48:40.050 --> 48:42.746
- What?
- Bloom, I know

48:43.020 --> 48:45.352
I'm pretending to be a smuggler.

48:47.124 --> 48:48.455
Right?

48:48.692 --> 48:51.160
But what you don't know is,

48:52.362 --> 48:56.162
I am a full-on smuggler.

48:57.668 --> 49:00.000
'Cause I tell it like I own it.

49:00.604 --> 49:05.667
You know what your problem is?
You just got to stop thinking so much.

49:06.176 --> 49:08.838
I mean, just enjoy the ride, man.

49:09.413 --> 49:10.675
I mean...

49:20.023 --> 49:22.617
I love thunderstorms.

49:54.157 --> 49:56.751
Oh, my God. I'm just so horny.

49:56.827 --> 49:58.522
Goodnight.

50:10.974 --> 50:12.805
Here's the big two.

50:22.352 --> 50:25.219
Last time I was in Prague, I was in love.

50:25.389 --> 50:27.084
What was she like?

50:28.658 --> 50:30.888
Pale skin, long feet.

50:32.696 --> 50:33.924
So...

50:35.799 --> 50:37.494
And that's mine.

50:39.736 --> 50:42.000
Bloom and I will secure lodging.

50:44.908 --> 50:48.071
Miss Yueng Ling will scout out the museum.

50:48.712 --> 50:50.077
You will go to the bank.

50:50.147 --> 50:52.843
That wire should have cleared
if you put it in at Athens.

50:52.916 --> 50:55.282
- Cash?
- No.

50:55.952 --> 50:59.820
Only movie thugs and Russians
deal in suitcases of cash.

50:59.890 --> 51:02.051
You're gonna get a certified check.

51:08.131 --> 51:10.793
Who the hell is that?
Who is it?

51:11.034 --> 51:12.763
A Candy-gram.

51:12.903 --> 51:14.666
Max, it's us, for Christ's sake.

51:15.772 --> 51:16.761
Whoa!

51:21.278 --> 51:23.473
- Max! Max, it's us, Bloom.
- Max! It's Stephen and Bloom.

51:23.547 --> 51:25.447
- Jesus, Max, easy...
- Jesus, whoa!

51:25.515 --> 51:26.914
Whoa, now!

51:27.050 --> 51:28.449
Yeah, yeah, yeah. Good morning.

51:29.586 --> 51:32.248
Come in. I have been drinking, you know.

51:35.459 --> 51:36.448
So,

51:40.130 --> 51:44.931
